<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-derivApp-opt" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Optimization Problems</title>

<objectives>
  <ul>
    <li>
      Identify and clearly describe the target quantity, controlling variable(s), and constraint(s) in an optimization problem.
    </li>
    <li>
      Translate a real-world situation into equations and reduce the problem to a single-variable function with an appropriate domain.
    </li>
    <li>
      Use derivatives to locate and justify absolute maxima and minima on closed, open, or unbounded intervals.
    </li>
    <li>
      Interpret solutions in context, including units, feasibility, and practical meaning.
    </li>
  </ul>
</objectives>

  <p>
    In many applications, we are not just interested in computing derivatives.
    Instead, we use derivatives as a tool to make the best possible choice:
    the largest area, the smallest cost, the least time, or the greatest profit.
    These sorts of real-world problems are called <term>optimization problems</term>.
  </p>

  <subsection xml:id="ssec-opt-motivating-example">
    <title>Motivating Example and Overall Technique</title>


    <example xml:id="ex-opt-rectangle">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Suppose we have <m>40</m> meters of fencing to enclose a rectangular area.
           What dimensions maximize the area?
        </p>

        <ol marker="(a)">
          <li>
            <p>
              Click on the Desmos model below to explore different rectangles, 
              build intuition about the problem, and develop a sense of what the final answer should look like.
            </p>
               <url href="https://www.desmos.com/calculator/6o2oojvp14">
      <figure>
<caption>
  A GIF showing various rectangles with a perimeter of 40 meters. As the dimensions of the rectangle change, the area is calculated and displayed. 
  The animation illustrates how the area changes for different length and width combinations, 
  helping to visualize the optimization problem and understand which dimensions yield the maximum area.
</caption>
        <image width="100%" source="images/Optimization01.gif">
<shortdescription>
  Animated graph showing rectangles with a perimeter of 40 meters. As the length and width of the rectangle change, the area is calculated and displayed. 
  The animation helps visualize how the area changes for different dimensions, guiding us towards understanding which dimensions maximize the area. 
  It appears that the area is maximized when the rectangle is a square, with both length and width equal to 10 meters.
</shortdescription>
        </image>
      </figure>
  </url>

          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Use calculus techniques to find the dimensions of the rectangle of greatest area.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol> 
      </statement>

      <solution>
        <p> (a) Experimenting with the Desmos model suggests that the rectangle of greatest area is a square with side length 10 meters. 
          We will confirm this using calculus in part (b).</p>
        
        <p> (b) To solve this problem, we first identify the controlling variables, constraints, and target quantity.</p>
          <p> Our target quantity that we are trying to maximize is the area of the rectangle (<m>A=\ell w</m>). 
            The controlling variables are the length <m>\ell</m> and width <m>w</m> of the rectangle. 
            The constraint is that the perimeter must be 40 meters.</p>
            <p> Using the constraint, we can express one variable in terms of the other and write the area as a single-variable function.
        </p>
        <me>\begin{array}{rcl}
          2\ell+2w \amp = \amp 40 \\
          \ell+w \amp = \amp 20 \\
          w \amp = \amp 20-\ell
        \end{array}
        </me>
  <p>         Using this we can express the area as a function of <m>\ell</m>:
  </p> 
        <me>
          A=\ell w=\ell(20-\ell)=20\ell-\ell^2.
        </me>

        <p>
          The physical domain requires <m>\ell\ge 0</m> and <m>w\ge 0</m>, so
          <m>\ell\in[0,20]</m>.
          Now we find the absolute maximum of <m>A(\ell)</m> on <m>[0,20]</m>.
        </p>

        <me>
          A'(\ell)=20-2\ell.
        </me>

        <p>
          The critical point satisfies <m>A'(\ell)=0</m>, so <m>\ell=10</m>.
        </p>
        <p>Since the domain is a closed interval, we can use the Closed Interval Method to check the endpoints and the critical point:</p>

        <me>
          A(0)=0,\qquad A(10)=100,\qquad A(20)=0.
        </me>

        <p>
          So the largest Area value occurs at <m>\ell=10</m> meters.
          Therefore <m>w=20-\ell=10</m> meters. And so we can see from this example that the rectangle of greatest area is a square with side length 10 meters, 
          confirming our initial guess from the Desmos model.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    
<p>
  Since we are interested in finding absolute extrema, it is helpful that we already have a method for functions defined on a closed interval, as in the previous example.
  However, what happens when the domain is open or unbounded? Up to this point, our techniques in those settings allow us to find only <alert>local extrema</alert>.
  For that reason, the following two results will be especially useful.
</p>


    <theorem xml:id="thm-abs-ext-first-deriv-test">
      <title>First Derivative Test for Absolute Extrema</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Suppose that <m>c</m> is the only critical point of a continuous function <m>f</m> on an interval <m>I</m>, then the following hold:
        </p> 
          <ul>
            <li>
              <p>
                If <m>f'(x)\gt 0</m>  for all <m>x\lt c</m> and <m>f'(x)\lt 0</m> for all <m>x\gt c</m>, then <m>f(c)</m> is an absolute maximum of <m>f</m> on <m>I</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                If <m>f'(x)\lt 0</m>  for all <m>x\lt c</m> and <m>f'(x)\gt 0</m> for all <m>x\gt c</m>, then <m>f(c)</m> is an absolute minimum of <m>f</m> on <m>I</m>.
              </p>
            </li> 
          </ul> 
      </statement>
    </theorem>

    <theorem xml:id="thm-abs-ext-second-deriv-test">
      <title>Second Derivative Test for Absolute Extrema</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Suppose that <m>c</m> is the only critical point of a continuous function <m>f</m> on an interval <m>I</m> such that <m>f'(c)=0</m> , then the following hold:
        </p>
          <ul>
            <li>
              <p>
                If <m>f''(c)\lt 0</m>, then <m>f(c)</m> is an absolute maximum of <m>f</m> on <m>I</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                If <m>f''(c)\gt 0</m>, then <m>f(c)</m> is an absolute minimum of <m>f</m> on <m>I</m>.
              </p>
            </li> 
          </ul> 
      </statement>
    </theorem>

    
    <p>Now let's summarize the overall technique for solving optimization problems.</p>



    <algorithm xml:id="strat-optimization-method">
      <title>Technique for Optimization</title>
      <p>
        Most optimization problems follow the same workflow:
      </p>

      <ol>
        <li>
          Draw a labeled picture (if appropriate). Identify the controlling variable(s),
          the constraint(s), and the target quantity you want to maximize or minimize.
        </li>
        <li>
          Write equations that relate the variables using geometry, formulas, or context.
        </li>
        <li>
          Choose one controlling variable as the independent variable and rewrite the target quantity
          as a single-variable function <m>T(x)</m> (in our previous example our target quantity was area). Determine the domain of <m>x</m>.
        </li>
        <li> <p> 
          Find the desired absolute extrema of <m>T(x)</m> on its domain by one of 
          <ul>
            <li>
              <p>
                The <xref ref="strat-extrema">Closed Interval Method</xref> if the domain is a closed interval.  
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                The <xref ref="thm-abs-ext-first-deriv-test">First Derivative Test for Absolute Extrema</xref> 
                if the domain is open or unbounded and the critical point is the only candidate.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                The <xref ref="thm-abs-ext-second-deriv-test">Second Derivative Test for Absolute Extrema</xref> 
                if the domain is open or unbounded and the critical point is the only candidate (and it is difficult to analyze the sign of the first derivative).
              </p>
            </li>
          </ul>
          
        </p> 
        </li>
        <li>
          Interpret your answer in context and check that it makes sense.
        </li>
      </ol>
    </algorithm>

      
<p>And with that we are ready to solve optimization problems! Similar to related rates problems, 
  the key is to practice the technique on a variety of examples so that you can recognize the pattern and apply it efficiently.
</p> 

  </subsection>




  <subsection xml:id="ssec-opt-examples">
    <title>More Examples</title>

    <example xml:id="ex-opt-bucket"> 
      <statement>
        <p>
          A 10-quart bucket has cylindrical sides and a circular bottom (no top).
          What is the minimum surface area for such a bucket?
        </p>

        <p><em>Hint:</em> 10 quarts is <m>\tfrac{1155}{2}</m> cubic inches.</p>

        <ol marker="(a)">
          <li>
            <p>
              Use the Desmos graphing tool to visualize the situation, the surface area function, 
              and approximate the optimal dimensions.
            </p>
               <url href="https://www.desmos.com/calculator/dqkdsx9x3c">
      <figure>
<caption>
  A GIF showing various cylinders with a fixed volume of 10 quarts. As the radius and height of the cylinder change, the surface area is calculated and displayed.
  The animation helps visualize how the surface area changes for different dimensions, guiding us towards understanding which dimensions minimize the surface area. 
</caption>
        <image width="100%" source="images/Optimization02.gif">
  <shortdescription>
  A GIF showing various cylinders with a fixed volume of 10 quarts. As the radius and height of the cylinder change, the surface area is calculated and displayed.
  The animation helps visualize how the surface area changes for different dimensions, guiding us towards understanding which dimensions minimize the surface area.
  It appears that the surface area is minimized when the radius is about 5.5 inches. At this point the Surface Area is around 300 square inches.
</shortdescription>
        </image>
      </figure>
  </url>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Find the minimum surface area. What are the dimensions that minimize surface area? Confirm that they minimize surface area.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>


      </statement>

      <solution>
        <p>
          The target quantity is the surface area
        </p>

        <me> \begin{array}{rcl}
           S \amp = \amp \text{area of bottom} + \text{area of sides} \\
           S \amp = \amp \pi r^2 + 2\pi rh
           \end{array}
          </me>

        <p>
          The constraint is the volume. Converting 10 quarts to cubic inches gives
          <m>V=\tfrac{1155}{2} \text{in}^3</m>, so
        </p>

        <me>
          V=\pi r^2h=\frac{1155}{2}.
        </me>

        <p>
          Use the constraint to write <m>h</m> in terms of <m>r</m>:
        </p>

        <me>
          h=\frac{1155}{2\pi r^2}.
        </me>

        <p>
          Substitute into <m>S</m> to obtain a single-variable function:
        </p>

        <me>
          S(r)=\pi r^2+2\pi r\left(\frac{1155}{2\pi r^2}\right)
          =\pi r^2+\frac{1155}{r}.
        </me>

        <p>
          The domain is <m>r&gt;0</m>. Differentiate:
        </p>

        <me>
          S'(r)=2\pi r-\frac{1155}{r^2}.
        </me>

        <p>
          Set <m>S'(r)=0</m>:
        </p>

        <me> \begin{array}{rcl}
           2\pi r \amp = \amp \frac{1155}{r^2} \\
           r^3 \amp = \amp \frac{1155}{2\pi} \\
           r \amp = \amp \sqrt[3]{\frac{1155}{2\pi}} \approx 5.69 \text{ in}.
           \end{array}
          </me>

          <remark>
            <p>
              Admittedly a calculator was used to get the 5.69 approximation above. However even without a calculator we can quickly and confidently 
              say this value is between 5 and 6 inches.
            </p>
          </remark>

        <p>
          The second derivative is
        </p>

        <me>
          S''(r)=2\pi+\frac{2310}{r^3}.
        </me>

        <p>
          Since <m>S''(r)&gt;0</m> for all <m>r&gt;0</m>, the critical point is indeed a minimum by the 
          <xref ref="thm-abs-ext-second-deriv-test">Second Derivative Test for Absolute Extrema</xref>.
        </p>





        <p>
          Now we can compute the corresponding height:
        </p>

        <me>\begin{array}{rcl}
          h \amp =\amp \frac{1155}{2\pi r^2}\\
          \amp =\amp \frac{1155}{2\pi\left(\sqrt[3]{\frac{1155}{2\pi}}\right)^2} \\
          \amp =\amp \frac{1155}{2\pi\left(\frac{1155}{2\pi}\right)^{2/3}} \\
          \amp =\amp \frac{1155}{2\pi}\cdot\left(\frac{2\pi}{1155}\right)^{2/3} \\
          \amp =\amp \sqrt[3]{\frac{1155}{2\pi}} 
          \end{array}
        </me>

        <p>
          Since this is the same value as <m>r</m>, we have <m>h=r</m>.
          This yields a bucket that is twice as wide as it is tall.
        </p>

        <p> Now to get the minimum surface area, we can substitute the values of <m>r</m> and <m>h</m> into the surface area function:</p>
        <me>
          \begin{array}{rcl}
          S_{min} \amp = \amp \pi r^2 + 2\pi rh\\
          \amp = \amp \pi\left(\sqrt[3]{\frac{1155}{2\pi}}\right)^2 + 2\pi\left(\sqrt[3]{\frac{1155}{2\pi}}\right)\left(\sqrt[3]{\frac{1155}{2\pi}}\right) \\
          \amp = \amp 3\pi\left(\sqrt[3]{\frac{1155}{2\pi}}\right)^2 \\
          \amp = \amp 3\pi\left(\frac{1155}{2\pi}\right)^{2/3} \approx 304.7 \text{ in}^2.
          \end{array}
        </me>
          
          <remark>
          <p>
            Real buckets are often designed with other priorities besides minimizing material,
            such as stability, ease of carrying, stackability, and manufacturing constraints.
            Optimization models are most useful when we clearly state what is being optimized
            and what is being ignored.
          </p>
        </remark>
      </solution>
    </example>




    <example xml:id="ex-opt-profit">
      <statement>
        <p>
          A company can produce phone chargers for <m>\$4</m> each and plans to sell them at an upcoming event for <m>x</m> dollars each.
          They have found that market demand is modeled well by <m>m(x)=100-2x</m>, meaning that when the price is <m>x</m>,
          the number of items sold at the event is <m>100-2x</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          What price <m>x</m> maximizes total profit for this event?
        </p>
      </statement>

      <solution>
        <p>
          The profit per phone charger is <m>x-4</m>, and the number sold is <m>100-2x</m>.
          Therefore total profit is
        </p>

        <me> 
          \begin{array}{rcl}
            P(x) \amp = \amp \text{(profit per item)}\cdot\text{(number of items)} \\
            \amp = \amp (x-4)(100-2x) \\
            \amp = \amp -2x^2+108x-400.
          \end{array}
        </me>

        <p>
          The relevant domain is <m>x\in[4,50]</m>, since selling below cost is not sensible here,
          and demand reaches zero at <m>x=50</m>.
        </p>

        <p>
          Differentiate:
        </p>

        <me>
          P'(x)=108-4x.
        </me>

        <p>
          The derivative is always defined, so there are no critical points from the derivative being undefined. 
          Therefore the only critical points come from setting the derivative equal to zero.
        </p>           

          <me>
            \begin{array}{rcl}
              0\amp = \amp 108-4x  \\
              4x \amp = \amp 108 \\
              x \amp = \amp 27
            \end{array}
          </me>

          <p> Because the domain is a closed interval, we can use the Closed Interval Method to find the absolute maximum by checking the endpoints and the critical point:</p>

        <me>
          P(4)=0,\qquad P(27)=1058,\qquad P(50)=0.
        </me>

        <p>
          The maximum profit occurs at <m>x=27</m>.
          The most profitable selling price is <m>\$27</m> per phone charger.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>




    <example xml:id="ex-opt-ants">
      <statement>
<p>
  A small insect starts at the lower-left corner of a <m>10</m> cm by <m>10</m> cm square of carpet
  and wants to reach the upper-right corner.
  It first travels along the bottom edge for <m>a</m> centimeters.
  From that point, it moves in a straight line directly to the upper-right corner.
</p>

        <image width="60%">
  <shortdescription>
    A diagram of a 10 cm by 10 cm square representing a carpet. 
    An insect starts at the lower-left corner and travels along the bottom edge for a distance of 
    a centimeters. From that point, it moves in a straight line directly to the upper-right corner of the square.
  </shortdescription>
    <latex-image><![CDATA[
\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=.5]
	\draw[fill=gray!20] (0,0) node {$\bullet$} -- (10,0) 
	-- (10,10) node {$\bullet$} 
	-- (0,10) node[pos=.5, above] {10 cm}
	-- (0,0) node[pos=.5, left] {10 cm};
	\draw[very thick] (0,0) -- (6,0) node {$\bullet$} -- (10,10);
	\draw[dashed] (0,-4pt) -- (6,-4pt)  node[pos=.5, below] {$a$};

\end{tikzpicture}
 ]]>
    </latex-image>
  </image>



<p>
  The insect moves at a speed of <m>1</m> cm/sec while traveling along the bottom edge,
  and at a slower speed of <m>\tfrac12</m> cm/sec once it begins crossing the carpet.
</p>

<p>
  (a) Find the value of <m>a</m> that minimizes the total distance traveled.
</p>
<p>
  (b) Find the value of <m>a</m> that minimizes the total travel time.
</p>

      </statement>

      <solution>
        <p>First it will help us to add a few labels to the diagram:</p>

        <image width="60%">
<shortdescription>
A 10 cm by 10 cm square. The insect starts at the lower-left corner and travels along the 
bottom edge a distance labeled a to a point on the bottom side. From that point, a straight line 
segment labeled b goes to the upper-right corner. The remaining portion of the bottom edge is labeled 10 minus a. 
The right side and top side of the square are labeled 10 cm.
</shortdescription>

    <latex-image><![CDATA[
\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=.5]
	\draw[fill=gray!20] (0,0) node {$\bullet$} -- (10,0) 
	-- (10,10) node {$\bullet$} 
	-- (0,10) node[pos=.5, above] {10 cm}
	-- (0,0) node[pos=.5, left] {10 cm};
	\draw[very thick] (0,0) -- (6,0) node {$\bullet$} -- (10,10);
	\draw[dashed] (0,-4pt) -- (6,-4pt)  node[pos=.5, below] {$a$};
	\draw[dashed] (10,-4pt) -- (6,-4pt)  node[pos=.5, below] {$10-a$};
	\draw[dashed] (10.1,0) -- (10.1,10)  node[pos=.5, right] {$10$};
	\draw (9.5,0) rectangle (10,.5);
	\draw[dashed] (10,10) -- (6,0)  node[pos=.5, above left] {$b$};
\end{tikzpicture}
 ]]>
    </latex-image>
  </image>

        <p> (a) The total distance traveled is the sum of the distance along the edge and the distance across the carpet.
          The diagonal segment across the carpet has length <m>b</m>.
          From the right triangle using the Pythagorean Theorem, we have
        </p>

        <me>
          b^2=10^2+(10-a)^2.
        </me>

        <p>
          Therefore
        </p>

        <me>
          b=\sqrt{200-20a+a^2}.
        </me>

        <p>
          The domain is <m>a\in[0,10]</m>.
          The total distance is
        </p>

        <me>
          L(a)=a+b=a+\sqrt{200-20a+a^2}.
        </me>

        <p>
          Differentiate: 
        </p>

        <me> \begin{array}{rcl}
           L'(a) \amp = \amp 1 + \frac{1}{2}(200-20a+a^2)^{-1/2}(2a-20) \\
           \amp = \amp 1 - \frac{10-a}{\sqrt{200-20a+a^2}}.
           \end{array}
        </me>

        <p>
          Set <m>L'(a)=0</m>:
        </p>

        <me>\begin{array}{rcl}
           0 \amp = \amp 1 - \frac{10-a}{\sqrt{200-20a+a^2}} \\
           \frac{10-a}{\sqrt{200-20a+a^2}} \amp = \amp 1 \\
          10-a\amp =\amp \sqrt{200-20a+a^2}\\
          (10-a)^2 \amp = \amp 200-20a+a^2 \\
          100-20a+a^2 \amp = \amp 200-20a+a^2 \\
          100 \amp = \amp 200 
          \end{array}
        </me> 

        <p>
          So there are no critical points from setting the derivative equal to zero. To make the derivative undefined, 
          we would need <m>200-20a+a^2=0</m>, which would require <m>(10-a)^2=-100</m> which is not possible since squares are nonnegative.
        </p> 

        <p> Therefore we have no critical points in the interior of the domain. Since our function is continuous on a closed interval, 
          we can use the Closed Interval Method and so we only need to check the endpoints:</p>
          
        <me>
          L(0)=10\sqrt{2},\qquad L(10)=20.
        </me>

        <p>
          Since <m>10\sqrt2&lt;20</m>, the minimum distance occurs at <m>a=0</m> cm.
          In other words, the straight diagonal is the shortest path (unsurprisingly).
        </p>


        <p>(b) Using (distance) = (speed) x (time), we can write time as distance divided by speed. 
          The distance along the edge is <m>a</m> and the distance across the carpet is <m>b</m>. 
          The speed along the edge is <m>1</m> cm/sec and the speed across the carpet is <m>\tfrac12</m> cm/sec.
        </p>

        <me> 
          \begin{array}{rcl}
            T(a) \amp = \amp \text{time along edge} + \text{time across carpet} \\
            \amp = \amp \frac{a}{1} + \frac{b}{1/2} \\
            \amp = \amp a + 2b\\
            \amp = \amp a + 2\sqrt{200-20a+a^2}
          \end{array}
        </me>

        <p> The domain is still <m>a\in[0,10]</m>. And the value for <m>b</m> is still <m>\sqrt{200-20a+a^2}</m> just like the first part. 
          Differentiate to get:</p>

        <me> \begin{array}{rcl}
           T'(a) \amp = \amp 1 + 2\cdot\frac{1}{2}(200-20a+a^2)^{-1/2}(2a-20) \\
           \amp = \amp 1 - \frac{2(10-a)}{\sqrt{200-20a+a^2}}.
           \end{array}
        </me>

        <p>Similar to the first part, there are no critical points from when the derivative is undefined (when the denominator is zero), 
          however we will see this time that there are critical points from setting the derivative equal to zero.</p>
 
          <me> 
            \begin{array}{rcl}
              0\amp = \amp 1 - \frac{2(10-a)}{\sqrt{200-20a+a^2}} \\
              \frac{2(10-a)}{\sqrt{200-20a+a^2}} \amp = \amp 1 \\
              2(10-a) \amp =\amp \sqrt{200-20a+a^2}\\
              4(10-a)^2 \amp = \amp 200-20a+a^2 \\
              400-80a+4a^2 \amp = \amp 200-20a+a^2 \\
              3a^2 -60a +200 \amp = \amp 0
            \end{array}
          </me>

          <p>Struggling to factor the left-hand side, we can use the quadratic formula to find the critical points.</p>

          <me> 
            \begin{array}{rcl}
              a \amp = \amp \frac{60\pm\sqrt{60^2-4(3)(200)}}{2(3)} \\
              \amp = \amp 10\pm\frac{10}{3}\sqrt{3}.
            \end{array}
          </me>

          <p>Only the negative root lies in the interval <m>[0,10]</m>, so we have one critical point:</p>
          <me>
            a=10-\frac{10}{3}\sqrt{3}.
          </me>

           <p>Since the domain is a closed interval, we could the Closed Interval Method to find the absolute minimum 
            but without a calculator it may be difficult to compare the values. So instead we'll try the First Derivative Test for Absolute Extrema. 
            We can analyze the sign of the derivative on either side of the critical point.</p>

            <me> 
              \begin{array}{rcl}
              T'(0) \amp = \amp 1 - \frac{2(10-0)}{\sqrt{200-20\cdot 0+0^2}} \\
              \amp = \amp 1 - \frac{20}{\sqrt{200}} \\
              \amp = \amp 1 - \frac{20}{10\sqrt{2}} \\
              \amp = \amp 1 - \frac{2}{\sqrt{2}} \\
              \amp = \amp 1 - \sqrt{2} \lt 0 \\
              T'(10) \amp = \amp 1 - \frac{2(10-10)}{\sqrt{200-20\cdot 10+10^2}} \\
              \amp = \amp 1 - 0 \\
              \amp = \amp 1 \gt 0
            \end{array}
          </me>

          <p>  Since the derivative changes from negative to positive at the critical point, the critical point is an 
            absolute minimum by the 
            <xref ref="thm-abs-ext-first-deriv-test">First Derivative Test for Absolute Extrema</xref>.
            Therefore the minimum time occurs at <m>a=10-\frac{10}{3}\sqrt{3} </m> cm.</p> 

            <p> For those who are curious, this is about 4.2 cm, so the insect travels about 4.2 cm along the 
              edge and then cuts across the carpet for the rest of the journey.</p>
            
        <remark>
          <p>
            Minimizing distance and minimizing time are different problems because the speed changes.
            The insect save time by traveling partway along the faster edge and then cutting across the slower carpet.
          </p>
        </remark>
      </solution>
    </example>

    
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="additional-worked-examples-opt">
    <title>Additional Worked-Out Examples</title>

    <p>
      To keep this section at a reasonable length, we include only a few representative examples directly in the text.
      If you find yourself stuck on a homework problem, or if you are studying before a quiz or exam, additional
      fully worked-out examples are available in:
      <alert>
        <xref ref="subsec-derivApp-opt">
          Additional Examples for Optimization Problems
        </xref>
      </alert>
    </p>
  </subsection>

  <exercises xml:id="exercises-optimization">
    <title>Practice / Study Problems</title>



  <exercisegroup>
    <title>Some True/False Problems</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        Determine whether each statement is true or false and briefly justify your reasoning.
      </p>
    </introduction>


<exercise xml:id="tf-opt-17">
  <statement>
    <p>
      In an optimization problem, units of the final answer are irrelevant as long as the numerical value is correct.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p>
      <em>False.</em> Units are essential for interpreting the answer correctly.
    </p>
  </solution>
</exercise>


    <exercise xml:id="tf-opt-00">
      <statement>
        <p>
        In previous semesters, students who identified a critical point and immediately claimed it was an 
        absolute maximum or minimum without checking could lose up to <m>50\%</m> of the points on quizzes / exams.
        </p>
      </statement>
<solution>
  <p>
    <em>True.</em> A critical point is only a candidate for an absolute extremum.
    Absolute extrema may also occur at endpoints, and some critical points are neither maxima nor minima.
  </p>
  <p>
    For this reason, it is extremely  important to justify why a critical point gives an absolute maximum or minimum
    by applying one of the appropriate tests. Clear justification ensures full credit on quizzes and exams.
  </p>
</solution>
    </exercise>




      <exercise xml:id="tf-opt-03">
        <statement>
          <p>
            If the domain is <m>(0,\infty)</m>, then an absolute minimum cannot exist.
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            <em>False.</em> An absolute minimum may exist on an open or unbounded domain,
            but we must justify it by analyzing critical points and either the First or Second Derivative Test for Absolute Extrema.
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>



      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Suppose that <m>x=1</m> is the only critical point for a function <m>f</m> on the domain <m>(-1,\infty)</m>. 
            If <m>f''(1)&gt;0</m>, then <m>f(1)</m> is an absolute minimum of <m>f</m> on <m>(-1,\infty)</m>. 
          </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <p>
            <em>False.</em> In order to conclude that <m>f(1)</m> is an absolute minimum 
            (and apply the Second Derivative Test for Absolute Extrema), 
            we would need to know that <m>f</m> is continuous on <m>(-1,\infty)</m>. 
            For example here is <url href="https://www.desmos.com/calculator/bfpwnzaqir">a Desmos graph of a counterexample</url>.
          </p>
          </solution>
      </exercise>

<exercise xml:id="tf-opt-04">
  <statement>
    <p>
      If <m>T'(c)=0</m>, then <m>x=c</m> must give either a maximum or a minimum value of <m>T</m>.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p>
      <em>False.</em> A critical point is only a candidate. It may correspond to a maximum, a minimum, or neither.
    </p>
  </solution>
</exercise>



<exercise xml:id="tf-opt-10">
  <statement>
    <p>
      If a cost function is increasing for all <m>x</m> in its domain, then the minimum cost occurs at the left endpoint.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p>
      <em>True.</em> If the function is increasing everywhere, the smallest value occurs at the smallest allowable <m>x</m>.
    </p>
  </solution>
</exercise>


<exercise>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Suppose that two positive numbers <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> sum to <m>10</m>. 
      Then the maximum value of their product <m>ab</m> is <m>100</m>.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p>
      <em>False.</em> Since the numbers sum to <m>10</m>, we know that</p> 
      <me> 
        \begin{array}{rcl}
          a+ b \amp = \amp 10 \\
          b \amp = \amp 10-a \\
        \end{array}
      </me> 
      <p> Therefore,
      the product is <m>ab=a(10-a)=10a-a^2</m>. In order for both <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> to be positive, 
      we must have <m>a\in (0,10)</m>. So <m>f(a)=10a-a^2</m> yields the derivative <m>f'(a)=10-2a</m>, which is never undefined 
      and is zero at <m>a=5</m>. So the only critical point is at <m>a=5</m>. Since the domain is an open interval, 
      we can use the First Derivative Test for Absolute Extrema.</p> 
      <me> 
        \begin{array}{rcl}
          f'(1) \amp = \amp 10-2\cdot 1 \\
          \amp = \amp 8 \gt 0 \\
          f'(9) \amp = \amp 10-2\cdot 9 \\
          \amp = \amp -8 \lt 0
        \end{array}
      </me>
      <p>  So the derivative changes from positive to negative at the critical point, so the critical 
        point is an absolute maximum by the 
      <xref ref="thm-abs-ext-first-deriv-test">First Derivative Test for Absolute Extrema</xref>. 
      Therefore the maximum value of the product is <m>f(5)=10(5)-5^2=50-25=25</m> (not 100).
    </p>
    </solution>
</exercise>


<exercise>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Suppose that two positive numbers <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> have a product of <m>10</m>. 
      Then the minimum value of their sum <m>a+b</m> is <m>7</m>.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution><p> 
      <em>False.</em> Since the product is <m>10</m>, we know that </p>
      <me> 
        \begin{array}{rcl}
          ab \amp = \amp 10 \\
          b \amp = \amp \frac{10}{a} \\
        \end{array}
      </me>
      <p> Therefore, the sum is <m>a+b=a+\frac{10}{a}</m>. In order for both <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> to be positive, we must have <m>a\in (0,\infty)</m>. 
        So <m>f(a)=a+\frac{10}{a}</m> yields the derivative <m>f'(a)=1-\frac{10}{a^2}</m>. 
        The derivative is undefined at <m>a=0</m>, but that is not in the domain. 
        Setting the derivative equal to zero gives <m>1=\frac{10}{a^2}</m>, so <m>a^2=10</m> and <m>a=\pm\sqrt{10}</m>. 
        Since we require <m>a\gt 0</m>, we have <m>a=\sqrt{10}</m> as the only critical point in the domain. 
      </p><p>
        The second derivative is <m>f''(a)=\frac{20}{a^3}</m>, so <m>f''(\sqrt{10})=\frac{20}{(\sqrt{10})^3}=\frac{2}{\sqrt{10}}\gt 0</m>, 
        so the critical point yields the absolute minimum.</p>
        <p> 
        The minimum value of the sum is <m>f(\sqrt{10})=\sqrt{10}+\frac{10}{\sqrt{10}}=\sqrt{10}+\sqrt{10}=2\sqrt{10} \approx 6.32</m>.
        </p> 
    </solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          The closest distance from the point <m>(2,0)</m> to the curve <m>y=\sqrt{x}</m> is <m>\sqrt{7}/2</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <em>True.</em> The distance from the point <m>(2,0)</m> to a point <m>(x,y)</m> on the curve is given by</p> 
          
          <me>
            \begin{array}{rcl}
             D \amp = \amp \sqrt{(x-2)^2+(y-0)^2} \\
             \amp = \amp \sqrt{(x-2)^2+y^2}\\
              \amp = \amp \sqrt{(x-2)^2+(\sqrt{x})^2} \\
              \amp = \amp \sqrt{(x-2)^2+x} \\
              \amp = \amp \sqrt{x^2-3x+4}
            \end{array}
          </me> 
          
          <p>
          The domain is <m>[0,\infty)</m>. The derivative is <m>D'(x)=\frac{1}{2}(x^2-3x+4)^{-1/2}(2x-3)</m>, 
          which is never undefined but is zero at <m>x=\frac{3}{2}</m>. Since we have only one critical point and the function is continuous, 
          we can apply the First Derivative Test for Absolute Extrema.
        </p> 
        <me>
          \begin{array}{rcl}
            D'(1) \amp = \amp \frac{1}{2}(1^2-3\cdot 1+4)^{-1/2}(2\cdot 1-3) \\
            \amp = \amp \frac{1}{2}(2)^{-1/2}(-1) \lt 0 \\
            D'(2) \amp = \amp \frac{1}{2}(4-6+4)^{-1/2}(4-3) \\
            \amp = \amp \frac{1}{2}(2)^{-1/2}(1) \gt 0
          \end{array}
        </me>
        <p> Therefore the critical point is an absolute minimum, and the closest distance is </p> 
          <me> 
            \begin{array}{rcl}
            D\left(\frac{3}{2}\right) \amp =\amp  \sqrt{\left(\frac{3}{2}\right)^2-3\cdot \frac{3}{2}+4}\\
            \amp = \amp \sqrt{\frac{9}{4}-\frac{9}{2}+4} \\
            \amp = \amp \sqrt{\frac{9}{4}-\frac{18}{4}+\frac{16}{4}} \\
            \amp = \amp \sqrt{\frac{7}{4}} \\
            \amp = \amp \frac{\sqrt{7}}{2}
            \end{array}
          </me> 
<p> as claimed. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </exercise>

    </exercisegroup>

  </exercises>


  <remark>
<p>
  There are relatively few True/False questions that effectively assess understanding of optimization.
  Because optimization problems typically require several steps and careful reasoning,
  they have historically appeared as standard response questions on quizzes and exams.
</p>
<p>
  For that reason, we strongly encourage you to complete your WeBWorK assignments
  and to practice with the additional fully worked-out examples available in
  <xref ref="subsec-derivApp-opt">Additional Examples for Optimization</xref>.
  These provide opportunities to strengthen your technique and check your work against complete solutions.
</p>
  </remark>




</section>